Enable the cv2 Python bindings when cross-compiling for Android and iOS, and
qualify OpenCV types with the cv:: namespace so the binding sources compile
under the stricter mobile toolchains.

OpenCV disables the python modules on ANDROID / APPLE_FRAMEWORK by default (see
modules/python/CMakeLists.txt and cmake/OpenCVDetectPython.cmake); we keep only
the WINRT guard so python3 bindings are still generated for our mobile targets.

The cv:: qualification is needed on iOS/macOS only: Apple's <MacTypes.h> defines
a global `typedef char* Ptr;` (and the bindings do `using namespace cv;`), so a
bare `Ptr<T>` is ambiguous with cv::Ptr. Likewise bare Size/Point/Rect clash.
We fix this in three places: the hand-written binding helper headers
(pyopencv_*/shadow_umat.hpp) are qualified directly; pycompat.hpp's CV_PY macros
use cv::Ptr; and gen2.py qualifies the code it GENERATES (prefix_ambiguous_ios,
including Ptr< nested inside other templates such as std::vector<Ptr<...>>).

Ported to opencv-python 5.0.0.93: OpenCV 5 removed the python2 module (so the
modules/python/CMakeLists.txt guard no longer lists python2), added more
bare-Ptr binding sites (cuda/videoio/shadow_umat and generated vector<Ptr<>>
returns) that this patch now covers, and dropped the old setup.py cv2.data
haarcascades install-path override (5.0 restructured cv2.data packaging).

